# In JavaScript, var, let, and const are boxes used to store data, but they have different rules regarding how their content can be changed and where they can be accessed. Think of a variable as a labeled storage box in your program.

📦 1. var (The Old, Careless Box)
var is the oldest way to make a variable in JavaScript.
It is very loose and careless, which often causes bugs,
so modern developers rarely use it.Can you change the value?
Yes. You can update it or even recreate the exact same box name
without an error.Where does it live? It has "Function Scope".
If you put it inside any curly braces {} like an if statement
or a loop, it escapes and can still be used outside of them.
It only stays trapped if it is inside a function.Real-world analogy:
A shared whiteboard where anyone can erase and overwrite everything
at any time.

#SYNTAX OF VAR

var price = 10;
var price = 20; // Re-declaring works fine! No error.
price = 30;     // Changing works fine too.
